snippet.textDisplay: As a cosplayer I understood this struggle so hard. Threading that damn machine is half the battle, and the other half is staying focused enough to actually sew straight. Cotton is the easiest to learn on as it's not super stretchy and is relatively easy to iron, which I would HIGHLY recommend to iron your fabrics during the process (gets those annoying wrinkles out!). Fyi, if you ever want a quick hem job for a nice finish just buy the iron-on hem tape for your clothes. Saves you the embarrassment if your stitches are as bad as mine. Keep it up, I think with practice you'll get better in no time! 😺

snippet.textDisplay: Hey Ryland, great job! I love the pants and shirt! I like sewing, too! I'm actually hand sewing the hem of a skirt right now. I loved watching you have the same thoughts I did when I made my first project. Your fabric choices are ambitious, however, I can't judge because my first project was a plaid tweed inverted pleat skirt. Ambitious sewing makes the best results, my skirt looks great and so does your suit. Velvet is tricky, but it makes a great end product. I suggest investing in a serger, people think they're scary but they do wonders for stretch fabrics and finishing raw edges. Get a t shirt pattern and you can whip up a jersey shirt on the serger in literally two hours, it's the most enjoyable thing to make. When working with velvet, always watch the nap. A great seam finish for it is lace bias binding, I had lots of trouble roll hemming by machine, so a bias binding is great. Maybe try using medium/lightweight interfacing on the jacket to give the fabric some structure, be cautious though since this will make it lose the stretchiness, a lining is another option to give it structure. Shoulder pads are fun. Scrunching at the sleeves may be caused by the basting stitches being too tight.
